The paper deals with action recognition using RGB-D data and proposes a series of 3D light-weight architectures. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category. Additionally, the paper proposes new architectures for action recognition, which involves machine learning and deep learning techniques, indicating that it could also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) and Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. The paper also deals with video data, which suggests that it could belong to the Multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category. Finally, the paper proposes models with lower computation cost, which suggests that it could also belong to the Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-category.
